# midi-daw — Project Overview

## What this is

A browser-based mini DAW modeled on FL Studio, built with Vue 3 + Vite. It has
four analog-style drum tracks, an FL Studio-style piano roll for MIDI
composition, per-track MIDI output/channel routing to external synths via the
Web MIDI API, and a jitter-free master clock. It can also run as a MIDI clock
**follower**, syncing to an external master (e.g. FL Studio set as sync
source) instead of generating its own clock.

The core value proposition is **tight, reliable MIDI timing** — every
scheduling decision should be made with jitter, drift, and note loss in mind.

## Engineering standards (non-negotiable)

All code in this repo — new and modified — must be:

- **Performant**: no work that isn't audio/MIDI-scheduling-critical should run
  on the same tick/frame budget as the scheduler. UI/animation updates must be
  decoupled from audio-critical timing (see `usePlayheadBeat` / `requestAnimationFrame`
  pattern below) — a slow render must never delay a MIDI event.
- **Scalable**: assume more tracks, more notes, more clock sources, and more
  UI panels will be added later. Don't hardcode assumptions (e.g. "4 drum
  tracks") into logic that doesn't need them — the project model should stay
  the single source of truth for counts/config.
- **High quality and well maintained**: fix root causes, not symptoms. When
  you find a timing/scheduling bug, explain *why* it happened in a comment,
  not just what changed.
- **Easy to contribute to**: prefer small, focused, well-named modules over
  large multi-purpose files. A new contributor should be able to find "where
  the clock lives" or "where MIDI gets sent" in seconds.
- **Modular**: engine logic (clock, scheduling, MIDI I/O, synths) stays
  decoupled from Vue components. Components should be thin — they read
  reactive state and call engine functions, not reimplement scheduling logic.
- **DRY**: shared behavior (e.g. reading the "current beat" for UI, converting
  a relative delay to an absolute MIDI timestamp) belongs in one place —
  a composable or engine helper — not copy-pasted across components.

If a change would violate one of these, prefer refactoring over shipping the
shortcut.

## Architecture

```
src/
  engine/            Framework-agnostic playback/MIDI logic (no Vue imports)
    clock.js          TransportClock — the internal master clock. Web Audio-based,
                       lookahead scheduler (SCHEDULE_AHEAD_SEC / LOOKAHEAD_MS),
                       emits 'start'/'stop'/'clock'/'step'/'scheduleNotes' ticks.
    externalClock.js  ExternalClock — follows an incoming MIDI clock (e.g. FL
                       Studio as sync master). Implements the SAME interface as
                       TransportClock (bpm, playing, beat math, onTick) so
                       consumers don't need to know which one is active.
    activeClock.js    Single source of truth for "whichever clock is driving
                       playback right now". Swapped between clock.js and
                       externalClock.js when Sync Mode changes. Every consumer
                       (scheduler, UI) reads through getActiveClock(), never
                       imports a concrete clock directly.
    scheduler.js       PlaybackEngine — binds to the active clock's tick events
                       and turns them into actual MIDI Note On/Off + clock bytes,
                       plus drum synth triggers. Owns note dedup and the
                       note-off timing-safety margins (see comments in file).
    liveLauncher.js    Live clip quantization + scene batch launch (shared
                       boundary so scene patterns land together).
    midi.js            Web MIDI API wrapper: device enumeration (with live
                       hotplug updates), sending messages (always as an
                       ABSOLUTE performance.now()-based timestamp — see
                       toAbsoluteTimestamp), and listening to MIDI inputs.
    drumSynth.js        Built-in Web Audio drum sounds (no samples).
  models/
    project.js         Plain-data project/track/note/pattern/scene model +
                       factory functions. Scenes are optional named groups;
                       patterns opt in via pattern.sceneIds (may be in many).
  composables/
    usePlayheadBeat.js  Vue composables that sample the active clock via
                       requestAnimationFrame, fully decoupled from the audio
                       scheduler's own timer — see "Performant" above.
  components/          Vue UI: TransportBar, DrumSequencer, PianoRoll,
                       LiveView (clip grid + scene buttons), MidiRouteSelect.
                       Read props/emit events; delegate all playback/MIDI
                       decisions to engine/.
  App.vue              Wires project state (reactive) to the engine singletons
                       and owns sync-mode switching + scene CRUD/launch.
```

## Key invariants to preserve

- **MIDI timestamps are absolute**, not relative. `midi.js` converts every
  relative delay to `performance.now() + delay` in one place
  (`toAbsoluteTimestamp`). Never call `output.send()` directly from elsewhere.
- **Note Off always has a small lead-out** before the next event (see
  `NOTE_OFF_LEAD_MS` / `MIN_GATE_MS` in `scheduler.js`) to avoid ambiguous
  same-timestamp Off/On ordering on retriggered notes.
- **UI redraws never run on the scheduler's timer.** Canvas/DOM updates driven
  by playback position must go through `usePlayheadBeat` (rAF-based), not a
  listener on the clock's tick events, or they'll compete with and delay
  MIDI-critical scheduling.
- **`getActiveClock()` is the only way consumers should read clock state.**
  Don't import `transport` or `externalClock` directly outside of
  `activeClock.js` and `App.vue`'s sync-mode wiring.
